Pages = {624-637},
Month = {APR},
Abstract = {Datafication is reshaping feminism, as feminist pioneers, groups and
   communities increasingly engage with data practices for advocacy,
   activism and social change. This is a netnographic study exploring how
   feminist actors in China appropriate the emerging technology of
   datafication to develop grassroots narratives for pursuing gender
   justice, focussing on two pioneering feminist collectives as key
   studies. The study begins by reviewing the role of gender data in
   women's empowerment within China's socio-political context, followed by
   an outline of the feminist data narrative concepts that combine
   Couldry's theory of data as narrative with insights from data feminism.
   Using these two cases, it illustrates how and why these collectives
   engage in data feminism to foreground gender justice. These examples
   demonstrate the ways in which data narratives offer transformative and
   empowering potential, generating new epistemic imaginaries of feminism
   in China. Ultimately, this paper underscores a paradigm shift towards
   the datafication of feminist narratives, connecting the contextual realm
   to the relational dynamics of data science for her social good.},
