Volume = {24},
Abstract = {This article argues that poetry is an act of meditation, improvisation
   and exploration, and urgency is what guides the writer into (and
   through) the poetic journey. In the light of this, this article
   illustrates the features of a workshop that was designed to guide social
   and human scientists in the delicate process of turning raw data into
   poems. One of the chief objectives of the decolonial project is to
   bridge the gap between Westernised academia ({''}The Ivory Tower{''})
   and communities where research is conducted, and this article aims to
   show how poetic inquiry is a fitting research methodology that can serve
   this purpose. Through a description of the workshop process and specific
   poems that emerged from it, it suggests that poetic inquiry is an
   innovative and effective research methodology for social and human
   scientists engaged in the transformation of conventional knowledge
